<p>In the latest development, a US- and Egypt-brokered ceasefire between Israel and Hamas held for a third day on Sunday, allowing hundreds of aid trucks to begin flowing into Gaza as displaced residents streamed back toward Gaza City [straitstimes.com#32][newarab.com#6][dawn.com#9]. Israel’s COGAT said the agreement envisions about 600 trucks of assistance per day, while Egypt said it was sending 400 trucks on Sunday; aid is being inspected at Karem Abu Salem and al-Awja, and Hamas officials said Rafah will reopen to individuals on Wednesday [scmp.com#10][newarab.com#6]. Hamas said it will start releasing Israeli hostages on Monday morning under a deal that will also see Israel free nearly 2,000 Palestinian prisoners; Israel’s prison service has prepared transfers ahead of the releases [lemo</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/uK1PVg39qnNr8h2kZk_SdC67h2lePxredxnvOpTNvJzalcMkHbEIk4IdX8CHuvqKrnzVKLM-7nnTd6iK5zNMAgv_tCckap8ObV-AJXl8' alt='Displaced Palestinians trek back toward Gaza City as the ceasefire holds.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Aid scale-up: COGAT expects around 600 aid trucks per day under the deal, with Egypt dispatching 400 trucks Sunday; shipments are being inspected at Karem Abu Salem and al-Awja crossings, and 90 trucks moved within the first hour [scmp.com#10][newarab.com#6].</li><li>Mass returns: More than half a million displaced Palestinians have returned to the ruins of Gaza City since the ceasefire took hold Friday, as bulldozers worked to clear rubble [dawn.com#9][aljazeera.com#11].</li><li>Exchange timeline: Hamas says it will begin releasing Israeli hostages Monday morning, while Israel prepares to free nearly 2,000 Palestinian prisoners as part of the first phase [lemonde.fr#24][france24.com#29][npr.org#15][timesofisrael.com#30].</li><li>Summit lineup: President Trump and Egypt’s President Sisi will co-chair a Sharm el-Sheikh summit with leaders from more than 20 countries, including France’s Emmanuel Macron and the UK’s Keir Starmer; Israel and Hamas are not expected to attend [thehindu.com#34][thehindu.com#36][politico.eu#43][newarab.com#38].</li><li>Security disputes: Israel vows to destroy Hamas’s tunnel network after hostages are freed, while a Hamas official says disarmament is “out of the question,” highlighting difficult talks ahead [theguardian.com#4][dw.com#23][straitstimes.com#12][straitstimes.com#33].</li></ul><blockquote>Israel’s great challenge after the phase of returning the hostages will be the destruction of all of Hamas’s terror tunnels in Gaza, directly by the IDF and through the international mechanism to be established under the leadership and supervision of the United States. - Israel Katz</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Israeli government: The priority after the hostages’ return is destroying Hamas’s tunnel network and demilitarizing Gaza through an international mechanism. (<a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2025/oct/12/gaza-ceasefire-live-aid-relief-hamas-release-israel-hostages'>The Guardian</a>)</li><li>Hamas: Disarmament is “out of the question,” signaling difficult negotiations over any demilitarization plans. (<a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/middle-east/hamas-official-says-disarmament-out-of-the-question'>The Straits Times</a>)</li><li>Egyptian presidency: The summit aims to end the war, boost peace efforts and usher in a new era of regional security and stability. (<a href='https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/trump-sisi-to-chair-gaza-peace-summit-on-october-13-egypt/article70154557.ece'>The Hindu</a>)</li><li>United States: The plan foresees an international force led by Arab and Muslim countries for Gaza security, a US-led reconstruction effort, an Israeli presence along Israel’s border with Gaza, and a potential eventual role for the Palestinian Authority. (<a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2025/oct/11/israel-gaza-ceasefire-hamas-hostages-netanyahu-trump-middle-east-latest-news-updates'>The Guardian</